Latin America in the fight against the Coronavirus.
SAO PAULO/SANTIAGO/BOGOTA/MEXICO CITY – The COVID-19 pandemic is a shock of unprecedented size and unknown duration.
The consequences are already catastrophic now.
If we do not face the crisis resolutely, it could become the most tragic episode in Latin American history.
So far, political reactions in our region have been very different.
Some governments reacted quickly and declared the protection of public health to be their top priority.
On the other hand, however, others unfortunately downplayed the dangers of the pandemic, provided their citizens with false information, and ignored not only scientific research, but also the advice of their own experts.
These state leaders decided in the midst of the tragedy to pursue a populist and divisive politics.
Latin America's top priority must be to keep the number of deaths as low as possible.
Politicians need to focus on improving the healthcare systems, equipping hospitals with resources, temporarily using vacant infrastructure such as hotels or conference centers, and significantly increasing testing capacities.
In addition, Latin American states must refuse export controls on medical supplies and other vital resources and push for additional resources for the World Health Organization (WHO) – in stark contrast to US President Donald Trump with his reckless decision to freeze around 500 million dollars in contributions to WHO.
We need a stronger global cooperation of health authorities to increase testing capacities, treat and isolate patients, and develop treatment options and vaccines – to finally end the pandemic.
The economic shock is enormous: not only was Latin American domestic production interrupted, but the countries there are also suffering from declining export volumes and prices, income losses from the missing tourism and fewer foreign remittances as well as strong capital outflows.
The supply shock in large parts of the economy could trigger a contraction spiral together with the collapse of demand.
To prevent this, courageous measures are required to protect household income.
This means transferring benefits to the victims of the crisis, including informal and independent workers who have no access to employment subsidies or unemployment insurance.
Relaxations for companies are also important.
Subsidies that help companies pay their wages and social security costs protect both them and their employees during the crisis. This makes them crucial for a quick economic recovery after the pandemic.
If the flood of bankruptcies is not prevented, the next victims of the pandemic could be the banks.
And at this point, the payment system – and with it the entire economy – is then endangered.
Many businesses, particularly small and medium-sized ones, will suffer significant income losses during the crisis.
Without support, the lack of liquidity will soon become a solvency problem.
Tax deferment, payment moratorium, and subsidized loans will not be enough.
This crisis requires not only unprecedented government guarantees to ensure that banks continue to lend money, but also temporary regulatory changes to promote credit expansion.
Even well-capitalized and well-managed state-owned banks can play a leading role in this regard.
Generally speaking, the measures will likely differ from country to country, but overall, extraordinary budget resources will probably be needed everywhere to accelerate recovery.
Governments must stimulate employment and economic activity without exacerbating the risks to health.
The problem is that the fiscal space in Latin America is even tighter today than it was after the global financial crisis of 2008.
Household burdens must also be cushioned by budget adjustments in areas of lower priority.
This involves the risk of downgrading creditworthiness, which can be reduced by the governments' promise to correct the higher budget deficits within an appropriate timeframe.
However, a pressing external support of households and balance of payments is required – especially for the small and less developed Latin American countries.
Both private companies and states are taking higher deficits, and it is likely that the current account balances of countries will deteriorate as well.
The most recent capital outflows from emerging markets – one of the biggest reversals in modern financial market history – are only making the problem worse.
The resulting currency devaluations can have a destabilizing effect.
In many economies of the region, the only way to cope with these mutually reinforcing shocks will be to receive a lot more external support.
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) plays a crucial role here.
He must attend to the short-term currency and budget requirements of the countries and continue to support their economies in this crisis, whose duration is highly uncertain.
To achieve this, he needs more resources and the ability to pay them out quickly.
Latin American governments should jointly call for a new edition of the International Monetary Fund's global reserve currency – the Special Drawing Rights, which should reach a volume of one trillion SDR.
Although SDRs are allocated to member countries based on their IMF quotas, a non-proportional allocation could be achieved by establishing a common pool under the fund's supervision.
In addition, the IMF could create the necessary capacity by immediately doubling the volume of the new credit agreements to meet the upcoming strong credit demand.
And finally, the fund must, since traditional IMF credit programs are not approved in time, improve access to low-cost tools with fast disbursement, such as its rapid financing instrument, or bring new credit facilities for the pandemic into being.
Major central banks that issue reserve currencies can help by expanding access to currency swaps – either directly or indirectly through the IMF or the Bank for International Settlements, which can further pass on the liquidity of central banks.
Domestic central banks must use all available instruments and, if necessary, create new ones to provide the financial markets and the economy with sufficient liquidity.
And ultimately, multilateral development banks (MDBs) like the World Bank, the Inter-American Development Bank, and the Latin American CAF Development Bank must double the volume of net lending in the region and tap into high-liquidity global capital markets to be able to provide further budgetary support.
In exceptional circumstances and in countries without market access, official lending might be supplemented by debt relief.
The MEBs should also provide guidelines to the countries on the different policy areas involved in crisis management, including their own estimates of the COVID-19 infection and mortality rates – particularly for countries where governments downplay the health threat.
In this case, Time plays a crucial role.
The challenge posed by this pandemic is unparalleled in recent history.
The world and the Latin American and Caribbean region can't afford delayed or inadequate responses.
Mutual trust, transparency, and reason remain the best guidelines in these uncertain times – and not populism or demagoguery.
The crisis must not serve as an excuse to weaken our hard-won civil rights.
Instead, it can serve as an opportunity to strengthen democracy in Latin America and show what it can offer to citizens.
